            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nThis text will explore how to perform consecutive sums — that is, multiplication — using the Chinese abacus (Zhōngguó, 中国), the Suanpan (算盤), and the Japanese abacus (Nihon-koku, 日本国), the Soroban. Therefore, we recommend studying the previous texts, in which we explained the use of these instruments, before proceeding:\n- **Adding with Soroban and Suanpan (算盤)**: we teach how to perform single-order sums using the abacus (<htcite0>).\n\n- **Practicing addition with Soroban and Suanpan (算盤)**: continuing from the previous content, we learn to perform sums involving more than one order (<htcite1>).\n- **Practicing addition with Soroban and Suanpan (算盤)**: in this text, we perform addition operations using the abacuses, with all steps described step by step (<htcite2).\n\nIn addition to the previous texts on the use of abacuses, we also suggest studying the text in which we explain multiplication through the *Yupana Inka Tawa Pukllay* method, developed by Dhavit Prem, which will serve as the basis for the approach presented in this text (<htcite3>; <htcite4>; <htcite5>).",
